<exercises><title> <em>Check your Understanding</em> </title>

	<exercise label="chkpts-general-integrating-factor"><title> <em>Answer-the-Following</em> </title>
	
		<task label="chkpt-general-integrating-factor-1"><title> <em>Purpose of the General Formula</em> </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					What is the main advantage of having a general formula for the integrating factor?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							It provides a systematic way to solve any first-order linear differential equation.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! The general formula ensures that we can always find an integrating factor for first-order linear equations.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							It eliminates the need to integrate when solving differential equations.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. Integration is still required to solve for <m>y</m> after applying the integrating factor.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							It only applies to homogeneous differential equations.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor method works for both homogeneous and nonhomogeneous equations.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							It can be used to solve any type of differential equation.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The formula specifically applies to first-order linear differential equations.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-general-integrating-factor-2"><title> <em>Standard Form Requirement</em> </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Why must a first-order linear differential equation be written in the form <m>y' + P(x)y = Q(x)</m> before applying the integrating factor formula?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							Because the function <m>P(x)</m> determines the integrating factor.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! The integrating factor is calculated using <m>P(x)</m>, so the equation must be in standard form first.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							Because it ensures that the equation is separable.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor method does not require the equation to be separable.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							Because it guarantees the equation has a unique solution.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. Writing the equation in standard form does not determine uniqueness.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							Because it removes the need for an integrating factor.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor is still necessary for solving the equation.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-general-integrating-factor-3"><title> <em>The Formula for <m>\mu(x)</m></em> </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					What is the general formula for the integrating factor <m>\mu(x)</m>?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\mu(x) = e^{\int P(x)dx}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! The integrating factor is found by exponentiating the integral of <m>P(x)</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\mu(x) = \int P(x) dx</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor involves an exponentiation, not just an integral.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\mu(x) = e^{\int Q(x) dx}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor is derived from <m>P(x)</m>, not <m>Q(x)</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\mu(x) = e^{\int P(x) y dx}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor does not include <m>y</m> in its integral.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-general-integrating-factor-4"><title> <em>Effect of Multiplying by the Integrating Factor</em> </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					What happens when a first-order linear equation is multiplied by its integrating factor?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							The left-hand side becomes a single derivative of a product.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! The integrating factor allows the left-hand side to be rewritten as <m>\frac{d}{dx} [\mu(x) y]</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							The equation transforms into a separable equation.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The equation is rewritten for integration but does not necessarily become separable.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							The integrating factor cancels out completely.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor is essential to rewriting the equation.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							The equation always becomes homogeneous.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor method applies to both homogeneous and nonhomogeneous equations.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

	</exercise>

	<exercise label="chkpts-deriving-formula"><title> <em>Answer-the-Following</em> </title>
	
		<task label="chkpt-deriving-formula-1"><title> <em>Purpose of Deriving the Formula</em> </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					What is the main goal of deriving the integrating factor formula?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							To find a general function <m>\mu(x)</m> that allows rewriting any first-order linear differential equation as a single derivative.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! The integrating factor formula is derived to ensure any first-order linear equation can be transformed for easier solving.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							To prove that all differential equations are separable.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor method is distinct from separation of variables.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							To eliminate the derivative term entirely.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor transforms the equation but does not eliminate derivatives.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							To convert any differential equation into a homogeneous equation.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor method applies to both homogeneous and nonhomogeneous equations.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-deriving-formula-2"><title> <em>Standard Form Requirement</em> </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Why must a first-order linear differential equation be written in the form <m>y' + P(x)y = Q(x)</m> before applying the integrating factor method?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							Because the function <m>P(x)</m> determines the integrating factor.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! The integrating factor is computed using <m>P(x)</m>, so the equation must be in standard form first.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							Because it ensures that the equation has only one solution.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. Standard form does not determine the uniqueness of the solution.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							Because it makes the equation separable.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. Standard form does not necessarily make the equation separable.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							Because it eliminates the constant term in the equation.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The standard form does not eliminate constants but organizes the terms properly.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-deriving-formula-3"><title> <em>Deriving the Integrating Factor</em> </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					How is the integrating factor <m>\mu(x) = e^{\int P(x)dx}</m> derived?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							By ensuring that <m>\mu(x)</m> satisfies the condition <m>\frac{d\mu}{dx} = P(x) \mu</m>.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! The function <m>\mu(x)</m> must satisfy this differential equation to correctly transform the original equation.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							By setting <m>\mu(x)</m> equal to <m>Q(x)</m>.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor depends on <m>P(x)</m>, not <m>Q(x)</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							By assuming <m>\mu(x)</m> is always equal to 1.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor varies depending on <m>P(x)</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							By solving for <m>\mu(x)</m> using the quadratic formula.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor is derived using an exponential function, not a quadratic equation.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-deriving-formula-4"><title> <em>Effect of Multiplying by the Integrating Factor</em> </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					What happens when we multiply a first-order linear equation by its integrating factor?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							The left-hand side becomes a single derivative of a product.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! Multiplication by <m>\mu(x)</m> allows us to rewrite the left-hand side as <m>\frac{d}{dx}[\mu(x)y]</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							The equation transforms into a homogeneous equation.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The equation remains nonhomogeneous unless <m>Q(x) = 0</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							The integrating factor cancels out completely.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor is essential to rewriting the equation.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							The equation always becomes separable.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The equation is rewritten into an integrable form, but it is not necessarily separable.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

	</exercise>

